The conjunction fallacy refers to the tendency to judge a specific condition as more probable than a more general encompassing condition. In this case, option (b) is a more specific scenario that includes the condition in option (a) ("The first book receives harsh critical reviews"), but adds an additional component ("but becomes a bestseller"). Logically, the probability of the more general condition (a) should be greater than or equal to the probability of the more specific conjunctive condition (b). However, due to representativeness heuristic and other cognitive biases, people often judge the more specific and seemingly more representative scenario as more likely.

Therefore, option (b) is the more probable answer exhibiting the conjunction fallacy, where people tend to overestimate the likelihood of the more descriptive and elaborate scenario.
